00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:01.910
But what this is
showing, then, is

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:08.039
trying to show how a wave varies
both in distance and in time.

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:11.220
So the wave's propagating
along this z-direction.

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:13.410
So if you look
along this z-axis,

00:02:13.410 --> 00:02:17.480
you will see this
amplitude variation

00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:19.290
given by the black line.

00:02:19.290 --> 00:02:22.460
So a cosine-type variation.

00:02:22.460 --> 00:02:28.220
And then at any point, any
value of z, you can see,

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:32.330
plotted in red, how the
amplitude will change

00:02:32.330 --> 00:02:36.260
with time along this axis here.

00:02:36.260 --> 00:02:42.170
So you can see that you
get a sinusoidal variation

00:02:42.170 --> 00:02:45.190
both in time and in space.

00:02:45.190 --> 00:02:52.870
And a reminder here, then,
how you can express this wave.

00:02:52.870 --> 00:02:57.200
This is a
sinusoidal-shaped wave,

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:59.890
which is moving in the
positive z-direction.

00:02:59.890 --> 00:03:03.700
And you can either express
it in this form, which

00:03:03.700 --> 00:03:07.180
is what you would actually
measure if you could really

00:03:07.180 --> 00:03:10.480
measure it-- except that, as we
said before, you can't really

00:03:10.480 --> 00:03:13.690
measure it because it's
moving too quickly.

00:03:13.690 --> 00:03:19.150
But normally we do
the manipulations

00:03:19.150 --> 00:03:23.560
on the expressions using this
complex notation because it

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:26.050
makes it easier to do the sums.

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:29.040
Yeah.

00:03:29.040 --> 00:03:31.660
So this is showing, then--

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:34.940
this is a particular
value of distance,

00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:38.140
then, and showing
how it changes here

00:03:38.140 --> 00:03:43.720
the value of the phase of
this cosine wave at the time t

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:46.780
equals 0 according
to the value of z.

00:03:46.780 --> 00:03:48.300
I guess what that's
trying to show.

00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:55.780
And then let's think
now what happens

00:03:55.780 --> 00:04:00.630
if we've got some plane
wave propagating along

00:04:00.630 --> 00:04:03.160
at an angle with the axis.

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:06.370
So here's this
wave coming along,

00:04:06.370 --> 00:04:12.490
which it's going along a line--

00:04:12.490 --> 00:04:15.970
the direction of the
propagation of the wave

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:18.190
is along this
direction, which is

00:04:18.190 --> 00:04:21.490
an angle theta with the axis.

00:04:21.490 --> 00:04:28.720
And so you can see that when
this wave reaches this plane z

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:33.160
equals fixed here-- so this is
some plane where we might put

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:37.030
a screen or detector
or something--

00:04:37.030 --> 00:04:41.290
you can see that the different
parts of this phase front

00:04:41.290 --> 00:04:47.510
are going to strike this
plane at different times.

00:04:47.510 --> 00:04:52.570
Or equivalent, you can say that
if you look at this plane here,

00:04:52.570 --> 00:04:54.910
this wave will experience--

00:04:54.910 --> 00:04:58.180
exhibit-- different
phase at different points

00:04:58.180 --> 00:05:00.200
along this line.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:04.390
And so this is what we're
looking at here then.

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:09.460
As it says here, the path delay
increases linearly with x.

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:12.040
So there'll be
somewhere where this

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:17.140
arrives at a phase of 0, which
I guess is this point here.

00:05:17.140 --> 00:05:19.870
And then on one
side, the phase is

00:05:19.870 --> 00:05:22.120
going to be positive
and negative, according

00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:23.980
to which way you go.

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:28.040
So mathematically, this
is how we express this.

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:34.900
So this is our wave, the
same as the previous slide,

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:39.080
but now the wave is moving at
this angle theta to the axis.

00:05:39.080 --> 00:05:40.180
So we get this term.

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:42.100
This is our-- you
remember, we expressed this

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:50.380
before as k.r for a wave moving
in general in a direction r.

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:58.620
And so this-- so we
could write this then.

00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:04.200
This is what is in terms of
our phasor representation.

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:10.000
So as before, we write this
as an e to the i type thing.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:11.710
And then we also--

00:06:11.710 --> 00:06:17.020
this e to the minus i omega
t, we just missed that out

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:19.680
for clarity, just
because we don't

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:22.070
want to have to write
that every time.

00:06:22.070 --> 00:06:25.210
So there's an e to
the minus i omega t

00:06:25.210 --> 00:06:28.210
understood that we don't write.

00:06:28.210 --> 00:06:31.690
And k, of course,
is 2 pi over lambda.

00:06:31.690 --> 00:06:38.870
So k is related inversely to
the wavelength of the light.

00:06:38.870 --> 00:06:43.600
And so this thing here,
this complex number here,

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:47.400
you could write this
as e to the i phi,

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:52.890
like this, where phi is the
phase of the wave, which

00:06:52.890 --> 00:06:56.520
is a function of position.

00:06:56.520 --> 00:06:59.520
And it can be written like this.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:03.690
So if we look at a
particular value of z,

00:07:03.690 --> 00:07:05.205
then this z is
going to be fixed.

00:07:07.800 --> 00:07:12.210
So this part, e to the i 2
pi over lambda z cos theta,

00:07:12.210 --> 00:07:14.100
is going to be fixed.

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:16.230
And the phase
variation is only going

00:07:16.230 --> 00:07:18.660
to be because of
this other part here.

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:29.750
So this is another example.

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:37.700
And so this shows spherical
waves or rather distorted

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:41.630
spherical waves they become
because of the advances

00:07:41.630 --> 00:07:45.290
in modern technology that
love to distort everything

00:07:45.290 --> 00:07:48.260
you draw and make
it so that it's

00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:50.290
not the right shape anymore.

00:07:50.290 --> 00:07:53.510
But anyway, this is
a point source which

00:07:53.510 --> 00:07:56.460
is giving out spherical waves.

00:07:56.460 --> 00:08:00.830
And you can see that here
we put our screen again

00:08:00.830 --> 00:08:04.130
or whatever it is
that z equals z0.

00:08:04.130 --> 00:08:07.430
So you can see that these
waves, as they travel out here,

00:08:07.430 --> 00:08:10.610
they're traveling a
different distance

00:08:10.610 --> 00:08:13.170
before they get to the screen.

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:16.920
So you can see that's
going to do two things.

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:22.040
One is, of course, the amplitude
is going to decay as 1 over r.

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:25.280
So the amplitude of the wave
when it reaches out here

00:08:25.280 --> 00:08:30.920
is going to be smaller
than the amplitude here.

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:34.370
But much more important
is the phase effect

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:38.539
because you can see
the phase actually

00:08:38.539 --> 00:08:40.039
might change tremendously.

00:08:40.039 --> 00:08:43.400
Because the
wavelength is so small

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:45.740
compared with
these distances, it

00:08:45.740 --> 00:08:49.040
means that you only have to
go quite a small distance

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:52.790
before you get a big
change in the phase.

00:08:52.790 --> 00:08:56.690
So that's what we want
to be able to quantify.

00:08:56.690 --> 00:09:00.200
And so here we're riding
our spherical wave,

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:02.250
just like we did before.

00:09:02.250 --> 00:09:06.480
So George has kept this the
same as he's said before.

00:09:06.480 --> 00:09:09.020
You'll notice that it's
got this funny pi over 2

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:14.350
in there, which he
introduced that before.

00:09:14.350 --> 00:09:17.630
It has the effect of making
this like a sine, of course.

00:09:17.630 --> 00:09:22.350
Something minus pi
by 2 is like sine.

00:09:22.350 --> 00:09:26.240
This is actually like
a sinc type function.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:30.260
And that's the reason why
that pi over 2 is there.

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:33.350
It's so that it
doesn't blow up when

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:36.380
you look at what
happens at x equals

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:39.980
y equals z equals t equals 0.

00:09:39.980 --> 00:09:41.780
If you didn't have
the pi over 2 there,

00:09:41.780 --> 00:09:43.400
you'd have horrible infinities.

00:09:43.400 --> 00:09:48.180
So you avoid those by
putting this pi over 2 there.

00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:49.290
And yeah.

00:09:49.290 --> 00:09:50.900
So this is the radius.

00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:53.160
r is just the square
root of x squared

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:57.090
plus y squared plus z squared.

00:09:57.090 --> 00:10:00.030
So this is kr minus omega t.

00:10:00.030 --> 00:10:03.650
And this is our r at the bottom.

00:10:03.650 --> 00:10:07.680
And now we make
an approximation.

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:10.080
The approximation
we're going to make

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:13.260
is that we're not actually
really looking at this geometry

00:10:13.260 --> 00:10:16.980
as shown in the picture, but
we're looking at the geometry

00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:20.430
when, actually, we're only
looking in a small region

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:22.470
near to the axis.

00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:26.370
What that really, in
physical practice,

00:10:26.370 --> 00:10:33.150
that means is that this
distance z0 becomes very large.

00:10:33.150 --> 00:10:36.000
We're a long way
away from the source.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:43.230
And so we can think of this
value z being a very large.

00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:43.730
Sorry.

00:10:43.730 --> 00:10:47.050
You understand my
funny English language,

00:10:47.050 --> 00:10:49.040
don't you, when I
talk about "zeds"?

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:50.840
What you call "zees."

00:10:50.840 --> 00:10:53.330
I just suddenly realized that.

00:10:53.330 --> 00:10:55.260
Anyway.

00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:59.480
So we've already had this before
in earlier lectures as well.

00:10:59.480 --> 00:11:05.660
This is a square root that
we can expand by the binomial

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:10.820
and assume that z is large
much larger than x and y.

00:11:10.820 --> 00:11:14.990
So you take out a factor
z, and the square root

00:11:14.990 --> 00:11:20.300
becomes 1 plus a half-something.

00:11:20.300 --> 00:11:24.330
And so eventually you
get this sort of thing.

00:11:24.330 --> 00:11:29.480
So that's what we do
inside this phase term.

00:11:29.480 --> 00:11:33.260
But the thing at
the bottom, we say

00:11:33.260 --> 00:11:35.330
we don't have to be
so careful with that

00:11:35.330 --> 00:11:39.540
because it's not so
sensitive to this amplitude

00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:43.900
because all it does
is just changes

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:48.890
the magnitude of the
wave by a small amount.

00:11:48.890 --> 00:11:51.500
Because we've said
x and y is small.

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:56.090
But up here, you have to be
more careful because we're

00:11:56.090 --> 00:11:59.540
talking about phases.

00:11:59.540 --> 00:12:02.690
So anyway, at the bottom, we
can just neglect the x and y.

00:12:02.690 --> 00:12:05.310
So that's where the z
has come from there.

00:12:05.310 --> 00:12:08.720
And when we do this
binomial thing on the top,

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:11.090
we get this
expression here then.

00:12:11.090 --> 00:12:16.520
So the dependence on
x and y, you can see,

00:12:16.520 --> 00:12:19.400
just becomes a
quadratic type term--

00:12:19.400 --> 00:12:22.530
x squared plus y
squared over 2z.

00:12:22.530 --> 00:12:26.210
And so this is what this
picture is drawing here.

00:12:26.210 --> 00:12:31.460
The path delay increases
quadratically with x.

00:12:31.460 --> 00:12:33.950
So as you go further,
this point here

00:12:33.950 --> 00:12:37.040
corresponds to the
center of the screen.

00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:43.050
And then as you go
further away, this

00:12:43.050 --> 00:12:47.850
increases with some parabolic
variation like this.

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:54.790
So that's doing it in
terms of the cosines.

00:12:54.790 --> 00:13:00.190
If we go in terms of the
complex exponentials,

00:13:00.190 --> 00:13:02.860
much the same sort of approach.

00:13:02.860 --> 00:13:07.060
You can just expand,
again, the square root

00:13:07.060 --> 00:13:08.830
inside the exponential now.

00:13:08.830 --> 00:13:10.990
Exactly the same, really.

00:13:10.990 --> 00:13:14.410
And you end up getting
this expression here.

00:13:14.410 --> 00:13:17.140
And so this is an
example now, you

00:13:17.140 --> 00:13:21.850
can see, of the power of
this complex exponential form

00:13:21.850 --> 00:13:32.390
though because this complex
exponential of here two, terms

00:13:32.390 --> 00:13:35.270
or it might be more
terms in general,

00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:38.510
you can just expand
them, can't you?

00:13:38.510 --> 00:13:41.210
You can just say that
multiplied together.

00:13:41.210 --> 00:13:43.710
Whereas if it was
cosine, of course,

00:13:43.710 --> 00:13:48.140
you'd have to remember all
these things-- cos of a plus

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:51.320
b plus c.

00:13:51.320 --> 00:13:53.580
Horrible.

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:56.910
I don't know why I'm
making funny noises.

00:13:56.910 --> 00:13:59.550
Maybe I shouldn't keep
getting too near the speakers.

00:13:59.550 --> 00:14:02.260
Is that what it is?

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:02.760
Yeah.

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:05.010
So with the complex
exponentials,

00:14:05.010 --> 00:14:07.290
we can break it up very simply.

00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:11.730
And this inside the braces,
then, is our phi before,

00:14:11.730 --> 00:14:13.240
or i phi.

00:14:13.240 --> 00:14:16.950
So we can say this is e0 e
to the i phi, where the phase

00:14:16.950 --> 00:14:24.540
phi has just got this parabolic
term, plus some constant term,

00:14:24.540 --> 00:14:26.740
which corresponds to
this, which corresponds,

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:28.705
of course to this distance--

00:14:28.705 --> 00:14:31.080
the phase that you get through
traveling in that distance

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:33.390
there.

00:14:33.390 --> 00:14:35.830
So that's how you
get a phase delay.

