00:16:24.810 --> 00:16:27.010
about the significance there.

00:16:27.010 --> 00:16:27.510
Yeah.

00:16:27.510 --> 00:16:31.080
So the point is, I
mentioned that there

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:36.000
is this modulus term,
intensity-type term.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.790
But this is a very weak change.

00:16:38.790 --> 00:16:42.810
So you can imagine, if you're
trying to do an experiment,

00:16:42.810 --> 00:16:46.740
to actually measure the
properties of that wave field

00:16:46.740 --> 00:16:50.970
by looking at the intensity
would be quite tough because we

00:16:50.970 --> 00:16:54.030
said that these two
terms are very much

00:16:54.030 --> 00:16:55.930
smaller than that one.

00:16:55.930 --> 00:16:59.820
So looking at the
phase of the signal

00:16:59.820 --> 00:17:05.829
is a much more sensitive way
to look at that wave front.

00:17:05.829 --> 00:17:10.000
And as it says, the
phase can tell us

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.849
all sorts of things
about the wave,

00:17:12.849 --> 00:17:17.349
like where the wave has come
from, how far it's traveled,

00:17:17.349 --> 00:17:22.510
the materials it's gone
through, and generally

00:17:22.510 --> 00:17:26.890
the optical path,
which you remember

00:17:26.890 --> 00:17:30.130
we had optical path
before, integral ndz.

00:17:30.130 --> 00:17:32.590
So that will change the phase.

00:17:32.590 --> 00:17:35.410
And so if we can
measure the phase,

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:39.870
we can find out information
about those things.

00:17:39.870 --> 00:17:41.660
The problem, though,
as we've said before,

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:44.630
is that the phase is not
something you can actually see

00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:47.690
directly, because it's so fast.

00:17:47.690 --> 00:17:49.520
So 10 to the minus--

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:52.370
10 to the 15 hertz is typical.

00:17:52.370 --> 00:17:53.180
Very, very fast.

00:17:53.180 --> 00:17:56.510
Much faster than you can
measure with any electronics.

00:17:56.510 --> 00:17:58.350
So how do we do this?

00:17:58.350 --> 00:18:03.260
We do it by some form
of interferometry,

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:08.150
which is basically mixing
it with a reference beam.

00:18:08.150 --> 00:18:13.670
And then you look at the
intensity of the interference

00:18:13.670 --> 00:18:15.200
between the two waves.

00:18:15.200 --> 00:18:18.410
So this is how we do it.

00:18:18.410 --> 00:18:20.810
So I said that
we're going to look

00:18:20.810 --> 00:18:23.000
at two types of interferometer.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.770
The first one is the
Michelson interferometer.

00:18:25.770 --> 00:18:28.610
So this is how you make a
Michelson interferometer.

00:18:28.610 --> 00:18:32.660
You get light from some
source and split it

00:18:32.660 --> 00:18:36.740
into two parts with
a beam splitter.

00:18:36.740 --> 00:18:42.110
And one of those beams is
what we call the signal arm.

00:18:42.110 --> 00:18:44.250
This is what we're going
to try and measure.

00:18:44.250 --> 00:18:49.310
So here, this shows this light
going through some object,

00:18:49.310 --> 00:18:53.660
and then being
reflected by a mirror,

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:56.780
and then coming
back to a detector.

00:18:56.780 --> 00:19:00.710
And then the other arm
is the reference arm.

00:19:00.710 --> 00:19:03.860
So this is going to
produce a reference signal.

00:19:03.860 --> 00:19:06.710
So effectively, we're
going to be comparing

00:19:06.710 --> 00:19:09.260
the phases in those two arms.

00:19:09.260 --> 00:19:11.580
So the reference
beam comes down also.

00:19:11.580 --> 00:19:13.880
So these add together.

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:17.150
So we can add them as phasors.

00:19:17.150 --> 00:19:18.890
This is for the reference beam.

00:19:18.890 --> 00:19:22.340
Ar e to the i phi r.

00:19:22.340 --> 00:19:26.960
For the signal beam we've
got As e to the i phi s.

00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:31.490
We add the amplitude because
we're assuming it's coherent.

00:19:31.490 --> 00:19:34.790
Maybe I ought to stress
that a bit, of course.

00:19:34.790 --> 00:19:39.020
So this is assuming that
this is a coherent--

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:42.740
these two beams a coherent
with respect to each other.

00:19:42.740 --> 00:19:50.120
So if you had light here from
a laser, that would be true.

00:19:50.120 --> 00:19:53.450
And we'll probably
come onto cases where

00:19:53.450 --> 00:19:55.850
it might not be true later on.

00:19:55.850 --> 00:19:58.010
Once we've got the
amplitude, then we just

00:19:58.010 --> 00:20:02.070
have to find the modulus
square to find the intensity.

00:20:02.070 --> 00:20:03.980
And if you remember,
there's actually

00:20:03.980 --> 00:20:05.840
a proportional sign here.

00:20:05.840 --> 00:20:09.520
There's some funny
constants with epsilon

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:14.260
a half and things, which we
just don't usually worry about.

00:20:14.260 --> 00:20:21.550
So these phases tell
us the optical path

00:20:21.550 --> 00:20:24.580
that the light has gone
through in these two arms

00:20:24.580 --> 00:20:27.260
in order to get to the detector.

00:20:27.260 --> 00:20:29.710
And so what we're
measuring is the difference

00:20:29.710 --> 00:20:33.580
in the optical path
in those two arms.

00:20:33.580 --> 00:20:36.740
And so this shows
how that can work.

00:20:36.740 --> 00:20:42.130
So this is an example where
these two waves arrive in phase

00:20:42.130 --> 00:20:43.180
with each other.

00:20:43.180 --> 00:20:46.780
So then they'll
add constructively

00:20:46.780 --> 00:20:49.730
and you'll get a big
signal like that.

00:20:49.730 --> 00:20:53.020
On the other hand, you could
imagine that they might not

00:20:53.020 --> 00:20:53.860
arrive like that.

00:20:53.860 --> 00:20:59.200
They might arrive in anti-phase
like this, in which case

00:20:59.200 --> 00:21:01.930
you can see the two waves
now are going to cancel out.

00:21:01.930 --> 00:21:05.200
And you're not going to
see now any interference.

00:21:05.200 --> 00:21:08.390
In practice, of course, it could
be anything in between here.

00:21:08.390 --> 00:21:08.890
All right.

00:21:08.890 --> 00:21:11.080
So as you change--

00:21:11.080 --> 00:21:15.460
you can change the relative
phase of this light

00:21:15.460 --> 00:21:20.800
by changing the position
of this mirror or the size

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:23.650
or refractive index
of this object

00:21:23.650 --> 00:21:26.410
that's in there, or the
wavelength of the light,

00:21:26.410 --> 00:21:27.397
or whatever.

00:21:27.397 --> 00:21:29.230
It's going to depend
on all of these things.

00:21:33.580 --> 00:21:37.330
So example, measuring distance.

00:21:37.330 --> 00:21:39.490
So we've said that
effectively what we're doing

00:21:39.490 --> 00:21:42.610
is measuring the optical path.

00:21:42.610 --> 00:21:45.490
So optical path depends on
a few things, doesn't it?

00:21:45.490 --> 00:21:48.580
Optical path depends
on the distance,

00:21:48.580 --> 00:21:51.340
it depends on the
wavelength, and it depends

00:21:51.340 --> 00:21:53.420
on the refractive index.

00:21:53.420 --> 00:21:56.080
So these are all things
that you can measure

00:21:56.080 --> 00:21:58.550
using this sort of system.

00:21:58.550 --> 00:22:00.650
So here it's talking
as an example.

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:03.230
There's no object
in this one anymore.

00:22:03.230 --> 00:22:05.790
So this is just free space.

00:22:05.790 --> 00:22:10.780
And so in this case,
then, what you can measure

00:22:10.780 --> 00:22:16.060
is the difference in the optical
path in this arm and this arm.

00:22:16.060 --> 00:22:17.200
And the optical path--

00:22:17.200 --> 00:22:19.740
well, the refractive index
is now the same in each,

00:22:19.740 --> 00:22:21.730
the wavelength's
the same in each,

00:22:21.730 --> 00:22:25.840
so you could measure
the distance.

00:22:25.840 --> 00:22:31.000
So this is an interferometer
for measuring distance.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:34.360
So where could you use this?

00:22:34.360 --> 00:22:38.500
Well, imagine, this might not
actually be a flat mirror.

00:22:38.500 --> 00:22:42.220
It might actually have some
structure there, in which case

00:22:42.220 --> 00:22:45.160
you could actually measure
what that structure is,

00:22:45.160 --> 00:22:47.830
or if it was a mirror,
you could actually

00:22:47.830 --> 00:22:51.820
use this to accurately measure
the distance of this mirror.

00:22:51.820 --> 00:22:58.060
How far away it is from the
instrument, so to speak.

00:22:58.060 --> 00:23:02.690
So the interesting thing--
another interesting thing--

00:23:02.690 --> 00:23:04.870
this is the Michelson
interferometer.

00:23:04.870 --> 00:23:08.440
And the Michelson
interferometer,

00:23:08.440 --> 00:23:12.040
as the name says, was
invented by Michelson.

00:23:12.040 --> 00:23:14.290
Well, I think he
probably invented it.

00:23:14.290 --> 00:23:18.010
He certainly has his
name attached to it.

00:23:18.010 --> 00:23:22.090
But he mainly used it
for measuring wavelength.

00:23:22.090 --> 00:23:26.000
So we'll come back to that after
I've gone through the matter

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:26.830
bit, actually.

00:23:26.830 --> 00:23:28.720
I think it's probably best.

00:23:28.720 --> 00:23:29.500
Anyway.

00:23:29.500 --> 00:23:33.070
So what we've said is we add
together these two phases,

00:23:33.070 --> 00:23:37.300
find the modulus square, and
then we've got to expand that.

00:23:37.300 --> 00:23:40.370
So this is a square of
a sum of two things.

00:23:40.370 --> 00:23:43.790
So we're going to get the square
of this, the square of this,

00:23:43.790 --> 00:23:50.210
and then we're going to
get some cross terms.

00:23:50.210 --> 00:23:51.940
And this is what
it comes out to be.

00:23:51.940 --> 00:23:55.615
The two cross terms, one
is the complex conjugate

00:23:55.615 --> 00:24:00.060
of the other, which means that
when you add them together,

00:24:00.060 --> 00:24:02.880
the final result is real.

00:24:02.880 --> 00:24:04.830
That has to be true,
of course, because this

00:24:04.830 --> 00:24:10.630
is an expression for intensity,
and intensity has to be real.

00:24:10.630 --> 00:24:14.110
And so we've written
it in this nice form,

00:24:14.110 --> 00:24:21.610
Ar squared plus As squared
plus 2 Ar As cos of something.

00:24:21.610 --> 00:24:24.730
And this thing
here, the something,

00:24:24.730 --> 00:24:29.590
is the difference between
the phases of the two beams.

00:24:29.590 --> 00:24:32.990
So this next line
puts it into a sort

00:24:32.990 --> 00:24:36.250
of general term, general form.

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:41.670
It's of the forms a
constant plus a cosine.

00:24:41.670 --> 00:24:47.600
And then these quantities,
i0 m and delta phi,

00:24:47.600 --> 00:24:51.320
you can also write in terms
of these other parameters

00:24:51.320 --> 00:24:53.880
we had earlier.

00:24:53.880 --> 00:24:59.640
So as it says, when
both paths are clear,

00:24:59.640 --> 00:25:02.790
then these phases
adjust directly

00:25:02.790 --> 00:25:08.400
proportional to the
distance ls and lr.

00:25:08.400 --> 00:25:13.800
And so the phase difference
is just k times the difference

00:25:13.800 --> 00:25:16.020
in the two paths.

00:25:16.020 --> 00:25:20.910
So therefore, if you
measure the signal,

00:25:20.910 --> 00:25:23.860
if you know what
the wavelength is,

00:25:23.860 --> 00:25:25.860
you can measure what the
difference in those two

00:25:25.860 --> 00:25:28.230
distances is.

00:25:28.230 --> 00:25:31.380
There's a bit of
a proviso there,

00:25:31.380 --> 00:25:36.060
which is quite a big proviso,
that you can only do this,

00:25:36.060 --> 00:25:38.970
of course, modulo 2 pi.

00:25:38.970 --> 00:25:44.040
So because this is a cosine,
it's going to keep repeating.

00:25:44.040 --> 00:25:48.030
And you won't know which
of the cycles you're on.

00:25:48.030 --> 00:25:52.410
So it means that interferometry
is usually very sensitive.

00:25:52.410 --> 00:25:59.040
You can measure very, very small
distances, easily much smaller

00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:00.720
than the wavelength.

00:26:00.720 --> 00:26:04.350
And people sometimes talk
about measuring hundredth

00:26:04.350 --> 00:26:08.400
of an Angstrom and
amazing small quantities

00:26:08.400 --> 00:26:10.480
using interferometry.

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:15.160
The LIGO project, I don't
know what they're claiming.

00:26:15.160 --> 00:26:18.780
10 to the minus 15 meters
or something they're

00:26:18.780 --> 00:26:24.345
trying to measure to detect
these gravitational waves.

00:26:26.890 --> 00:26:27.540
Anyway.

00:26:27.540 --> 00:26:29.680
Yeah.

00:26:29.680 --> 00:26:33.200
So you only measure
it modulo 2 pi.

00:26:33.200 --> 00:26:36.410
So that means that if you're
trying to use this method

00:26:36.410 --> 00:26:39.470
to measure-- for
example, I'm looking

00:26:39.470 --> 00:26:42.680
at the door at the back
of the lecture theater.

00:26:42.680 --> 00:26:44.180
If I'm trying to
use this to measure

00:26:44.180 --> 00:26:48.860
the distance of that door,
I can measure the distance

00:26:48.860 --> 00:26:51.920
to an accuracy,
maybe, of something

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:53.960
smaller than a micron.

00:26:53.960 --> 00:26:58.840
But I wouldn't really know
whether it had added to that 10

00:26:58.840 --> 00:27:01.250
meters or whatever.

00:27:01.250 --> 00:27:05.330
So that actually has been what--

00:27:05.330 --> 00:27:07.280
a lot of people have
put effort into trying

00:27:07.280 --> 00:27:09.770
to develop interferometric
methods that you

00:27:09.770 --> 00:27:15.560
can get that extra information
so that you can actually

00:27:15.560 --> 00:27:18.880
do what we call unwrapping,
because this is like--

00:27:18.880 --> 00:27:21.930
they sometimes call
this phase wrapping.

00:27:21.930 --> 00:27:24.680
The phase wraps
because of the cosine.

00:27:24.680 --> 00:27:28.140
And so you don't know which
of these lobes you're on.

00:27:28.140 --> 00:27:28.710
Yeah.

00:27:28.710 --> 00:27:32.140
Well, going back to Michelson.

00:27:32.140 --> 00:27:35.730
So Michelson did this
the other way around.

00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:40.400
He knows this distance
and uses this expression

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:45.910
to find the wavelength or
the k value or whatever.

00:27:45.910 --> 00:27:48.770
And that's, of course, what
you do in an interferometer,

00:27:48.770 --> 00:27:49.970
isn't it?

00:27:49.970 --> 00:27:53.510
If you do a Fourier
transform interferometer,

00:27:53.510 --> 00:27:58.970
you're using that as
a way of measuring

00:27:58.970 --> 00:28:01.880
the wavelength of the light.

00:28:01.880 --> 00:28:07.370
In the case of Michelson,
he looked at various things.

00:28:07.370 --> 00:28:11.060
He didn't look at lasers because
there weren't any lasers then.

00:28:11.060 --> 00:28:14.600
But he looked at light
from discharge tubes

00:28:14.600 --> 00:28:17.970
and various different
types of lamp and so on.

00:28:17.970 --> 00:28:21.140
And he looked at
how the signal would

00:28:21.140 --> 00:28:24.610
vary as you move this mirror.

00:28:24.610 --> 00:28:27.870
And it turns out that if
you do move the mirror

00:28:27.870 --> 00:28:30.630
and you know accurately how
you're moving the mirror,

00:28:30.630 --> 00:28:33.150
you can actually
work out from that

00:28:33.150 --> 00:28:37.920
what the spectral
distribution of the source is.

00:28:37.920 --> 00:28:46.120
That also suggests a way
around this wrapping problem.

00:28:46.120 --> 00:28:49.390
The way around the wrap or a
way around the wrapping problem

00:28:49.390 --> 00:28:51.700
is to use not just one
wavelength but many

00:28:51.700 --> 00:28:53.150
wavelengths.

00:28:53.150 --> 00:28:56.380
So even two wavelengths
is a big help, actually.

00:29:04.730 --> 00:29:05.230
Yeah.

00:29:05.230 --> 00:29:07.330
It's quite interesting
that Michelson--

00:29:07.330 --> 00:29:09.670
I think I've spoken about
this with some of my students

00:29:09.670 --> 00:29:12.970
before, that Michelson, he wrote
quite a lot about measuring

00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:15.700
wavelengths using
that interferometer.

00:29:15.700 --> 00:29:20.200
And then many, many
years later, people

00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:24.370
came up with this
bright idea of using

00:29:24.370 --> 00:29:26.980
what they call the low
coherence interferometer

00:29:26.980 --> 00:29:29.380
or the white light
interferometer

00:29:29.380 --> 00:29:31.030
to measure distances.

00:29:31.030 --> 00:29:36.130
But as far as I know,
Michelson never suggested this.

00:29:36.130 --> 00:29:38.780
I've never found it in
any of these papers.

00:29:38.780 --> 00:29:39.280
Anyway.

00:29:39.280 --> 00:29:41.800
So this is another application.

00:29:41.800 --> 00:29:45.370
Here we're going to
look at a real object

00:29:45.370 --> 00:29:48.080
that we put in there and try
and find out something about it.

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:53.910
So we put in this lump
of material, length

00:29:53.910 --> 00:29:57.010
l, a certain refractive index.

00:29:57.010 --> 00:30:02.220
And you can see now then that
the phase of this light when

00:30:02.220 --> 00:30:09.480
it gets there is going to be
changed by the light traveling

00:30:09.480 --> 00:30:11.490
through that material.

00:30:11.490 --> 00:30:18.760
And have we taken
into account, George,

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:23.710
that it's gone
through twice here,

00:30:23.710 --> 00:30:25.020
or even on the previous one?

00:30:29.580 --> 00:30:31.560
There ought to be a 2 in there.

00:30:31.560 --> 00:30:34.520
There ought to be a 2
in here, oughtn't there?

00:30:34.520 --> 00:30:35.020
All right.

00:30:35.020 --> 00:30:39.760
So the phase difference
is actually twice this

00:30:39.760 --> 00:30:44.650
because it has this amount of
phase difference on the way

00:30:44.650 --> 00:30:47.880
in and on the way out.

00:30:47.880 --> 00:30:50.200
So I hadn't noticed
that before either.

00:30:50.200 --> 00:30:53.500
But it applies to
this next one as well.

00:30:53.500 --> 00:30:58.940
So this one, the light goes
through this object here.

00:30:58.940 --> 00:31:02.030
And so there's this
extra phase delay

00:31:02.030 --> 00:31:05.790
that comes because of this
object, which is this bit here.

00:31:05.790 --> 00:31:07.610
So again, there ought
to be a factor of 2

00:31:07.610 --> 00:31:09.890
for all of these terms.

00:31:09.890 --> 00:31:13.010
And so there we are, though.

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:16.970
We've got this
extra optical path

00:31:16.970 --> 00:31:22.880
and so now we can measure the
optical path of that object.

00:31:22.880 --> 00:31:26.160
Again, modulo 2 pi.

00:31:26.160 --> 00:31:31.110
So if this is many
wavelengths, you

00:31:31.110 --> 00:31:34.920
might have trouble
to know exactly how

00:31:34.920 --> 00:31:38.230
long it is, of course, because
of the wrapping of the phase

00:31:38.230 --> 00:31:38.730
again.

00:31:42.540 --> 00:31:49.530
So this modulo 2 pi we
can actually measure--

00:31:49.530 --> 00:31:51.800
this is the optical
path difference.

00:31:51.800 --> 00:31:54.330
n minus 1 times L.

00:31:54.330 --> 00:31:57.330
The minus, of course,
is because the other--

00:31:57.330 --> 00:31:59.310
the reference beam
has gone through air

00:31:59.310 --> 00:32:01.470
when this has gone
through this material.

00:32:01.470 --> 00:32:07.020
So what we measure is n minus 1
times L. If you knew what n is,

00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:09.570
we can know what L is.

00:32:09.570 --> 00:32:13.140
If we knew what L is,
we could know what n is.

00:32:13.140 --> 00:32:17.010
But as it says there, if
you don't know either,

00:32:17.010 --> 00:32:18.740
then you can't find either.

00:32:18.740 --> 00:32:23.100
All you know is
what n minus 1 L is.

00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:26.550
Anyone got any ideas
about how you might--

00:32:26.550 --> 00:32:29.700
what might you do
to get both of those

00:32:29.700 --> 00:32:33.430
if you wanted to
know both of those?

00:32:33.430 --> 00:32:36.170
Any ideas how you could do that?

00:32:36.170 --> 00:32:39.947
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:39.947 --> 00:32:41.530
COLIN SHEPPARD: Based
on what, though?

00:32:41.530 --> 00:32:44.440
You'd have to have
two measurements.

00:32:44.440 --> 00:32:46.963
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Press the button, please.

00:32:46.963 --> 00:32:52.390
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] Yeah.

00:32:52.390 --> 00:32:54.702
Someone says it's to use
two wavelengths to set up

00:32:54.702 --> 00:32:55.660
simultaneous equations.

00:32:55.660 --> 00:32:56.350
COLIN SHEPPARD: Exactly.

00:32:56.350 --> 00:32:56.880
Good one.

00:32:56.880 --> 00:32:57.380
Yeah.

00:32:57.380 --> 00:32:58.613
Who said it?

00:32:58.613 --> 00:32:59.780
Someone in the back said it.

00:32:59.780 --> 00:33:01.200
AUDIENCE: I heard it somewhere.

00:33:01.200 --> 00:33:02.030
COLIN SHEPPARD:
You're not getting

00:33:02.030 --> 00:33:03.072
the full credit for that.

00:33:03.072 --> 00:33:03.697
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:33:03.697 --> 00:33:04.240
Yeah.

00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:06.340
COLIN SHEPPARD:
Anyway, someone got it.

00:33:06.340 --> 00:33:07.090
So yeah.

00:33:07.090 --> 00:33:11.680
So if you measured this for
two different wavelengths,

00:33:11.680 --> 00:33:14.500
then you could have a pair
of simultaneous equations,

00:33:14.500 --> 00:33:18.070
and you could solve
for both of those.

00:33:18.070 --> 00:33:22.480
That, of course, assuming
that there is no dispersion.

00:33:22.480 --> 00:33:26.550
If n changes with
wavelength, then you

00:33:26.550 --> 00:33:28.960
are still back to square
one, unless you do

00:33:28.960 --> 00:33:31.670
some more wavelengths I guess.

00:33:31.670 --> 00:33:32.490
But anyway, yeah.

00:33:32.490 --> 00:33:34.900
So it just shows
you, though, you

00:33:34.900 --> 00:33:39.530
can do a lot of these
experiments very easily.

00:33:39.530 --> 00:33:41.260
So now let's sort
of-- these are used--

00:33:41.260 --> 00:33:44.120
this Michelson
interferometer is used

00:33:44.120 --> 00:33:49.060
a lot in metrology,
industrial sort of metrology.

00:33:49.060 --> 00:33:54.310
And all countries have their--

00:33:54.310 --> 00:33:56.500
in the US, it used to
be called the National

00:33:56.500 --> 00:33:58.030
Bureau of Standards, didn't it?

00:33:58.030 --> 00:34:00.595
But I don't know that
that exists anymore.

00:34:00.595 --> 00:34:01.720
AUDIENCE: It's called NIST.

00:34:01.720 --> 00:34:02.320
COLIN SHEPPARD: NIST.

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:02.820
NIST.

00:34:02.820 --> 00:34:04.070
That's right.

00:34:04.070 --> 00:34:04.570
It changed.

00:34:04.570 --> 00:34:06.350
I don't know why it
changed its name.

00:34:06.350 --> 00:34:08.920
But anyway, so all
countries have got this.

00:34:08.920 --> 00:34:14.409
They have this
standard measures.

00:34:14.409 --> 00:34:18.100
They have procedures for
calibrating distances

00:34:18.100 --> 00:34:19.760
and so on.

00:34:19.760 --> 00:34:25.900
And the idea is that if a
company like General Motors

00:34:25.900 --> 00:34:33.940
is making parts for a
car, that those parts will

00:34:33.940 --> 00:34:39.280
fit as a spare for another car
that's made by another factory.

00:34:43.790 --> 00:34:47.440
So say you make
some shaft that's

00:34:47.440 --> 00:34:51.699
supposed to be 1
inch in diameter,

00:34:51.699 --> 00:34:56.440
you want it to be
accurately 1 inch diameter.

00:34:56.440 --> 00:34:59.230
Otherwise, the
bit from one place

00:34:59.230 --> 00:35:01.630
wouldn't fit the
bit from the other.

00:35:01.630 --> 00:35:04.290
There is actually a
true story about that.

00:35:04.290 --> 00:35:06.060
A thing called the Vickers inch.

00:35:06.060 --> 00:35:09.550
Vickers is an engineering
company in the UK.

00:35:09.550 --> 00:35:13.990
And this Vickers
inch was a big thing

00:35:13.990 --> 00:35:16.840
that came up during
the Second World War,

00:35:16.840 --> 00:35:19.780
where lots of
factories all over UK

00:35:19.780 --> 00:35:23.140
were converted to
make munitions.

00:35:23.140 --> 00:35:27.250
And somewhere down
the line, people

00:35:27.250 --> 00:35:30.430
realized that Vickers had a
different inch from everyone

00:35:30.430 --> 00:35:32.080
else.

00:35:32.080 --> 00:35:34.690
So when they made
a shell and tried

00:35:34.690 --> 00:35:39.300
putting it in the barrel of
the gun, it didn't quite fit.

00:35:39.300 --> 00:35:42.130
So eventually that
was sorted out.

00:35:42.130 --> 00:35:44.750
They worked out what
the problem was.

00:35:44.750 --> 00:35:48.280
And I guess it's that sort
of problem that makes it

00:35:48.280 --> 00:35:50.720
so that the companies now--

00:35:50.720 --> 00:35:54.650
obviously the countries keep
these standards and so on.

00:35:54.650 --> 00:35:58.210
So the sort of
thing you might do

00:35:58.210 --> 00:36:00.540
is measure the height of this.

00:36:00.540 --> 00:36:02.860
Let's say you put in--

00:36:02.860 --> 00:36:05.338
they have these things
called gauge blocks.

00:36:05.338 --> 00:36:06.880
A lot of you are
mechanical engineers

00:36:06.880 --> 00:36:08.900
so you must know
about gauge blocks.

00:36:08.900 --> 00:36:12.760
So you can buy these
standard lumps of metal that

00:36:12.760 --> 00:36:14.870
have got a certain thickness.

00:36:14.870 --> 00:36:18.850
And so you put this
lump of metal in here

00:36:18.850 --> 00:36:21.886
and measure the thickness of
it using an interferometer.

00:36:24.780 --> 00:36:27.310
So these standards,
of course, they

00:36:27.310 --> 00:36:29.260
have these what they
call primary standards,

00:36:29.260 --> 00:36:32.320
and then they're handed down.

00:36:32.320 --> 00:36:36.250
I'm not quite sure how
the length works anymore,

00:36:36.250 --> 00:36:39.070
but it's all defined in terms
of the wavelength of something,

00:36:39.070 --> 00:36:41.570
isn't it?

00:36:41.570 --> 00:36:44.350
And then all of the
countries around the world,

00:36:44.350 --> 00:36:47.890
they all have to
compare their meter

00:36:47.890 --> 00:36:51.300
to make sure that they've
all got the same meter.

00:36:51.300 --> 00:36:53.050
And then within each country--

00:36:53.050 --> 00:36:58.710
so in the US, NIST would then
be measuring these gauge blocks

00:36:58.710 --> 00:37:02.430
that would be sent to
them from other companies

00:37:02.430 --> 00:37:05.430
to make sure that they've
got the right size.

00:37:05.430 --> 00:37:07.140
And then in the
companies, then they

00:37:07.140 --> 00:37:13.320
would compare those gauge
blocks against other gauge

00:37:13.320 --> 00:37:15.720
blocks and other things.

00:37:15.720 --> 00:37:20.540
So this is what you use-- one
of the things you use this for.

00:37:20.540 --> 00:37:23.280
So now, fringe visibility.

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:23.780
Yeah.

00:37:23.780 --> 00:37:26.638
So we've said that
you get these fringes.

00:37:26.638 --> 00:37:28.930
Perhaps I ought to go back
and explain that a bit more.

00:37:32.210 --> 00:37:34.670
Back to this one.

00:37:34.670 --> 00:37:37.990
So you can see here
we've got a constant term

00:37:37.990 --> 00:37:42.370
plus a sinusoidal-type term
or cosinusoidal-type term.

00:37:42.370 --> 00:37:49.180
And you can see that this
term m is called the contrast

00:37:49.180 --> 00:37:51.160
or fringe visibility.

00:37:51.160 --> 00:37:55.720
So if m is 1, then you can see
that they are going to be--

00:37:55.720 --> 00:37:59.020
for particular
values of delta phi,

00:37:59.020 --> 00:38:02.780
this intensity is
going to go to 0.

00:38:02.780 --> 00:38:04.740
So that's when you get--

00:38:04.740 --> 00:38:08.500
you've got very high
fringe visibility.

00:38:08.500 --> 00:38:10.600
And you can see
that this visibility

00:38:10.600 --> 00:38:18.610
depends on this, Ar 2 Ar As
over ir squared plus As squared.

00:38:18.610 --> 00:38:20.890
And you can show
quite easily that that

00:38:20.890 --> 00:38:24.600
is going to reach a maximum.

00:38:24.600 --> 00:38:28.690
It's going to be equal
to 1 when Ar equals As.

00:38:28.690 --> 00:38:32.500
So if you ensure
that Ar equals As,

00:38:32.500 --> 00:38:36.820
then you're going to get
your visibility of 1.

00:38:36.820 --> 00:38:39.190
I guess it can't be bigger
than 1 because that would

00:38:39.190 --> 00:38:43.070
mean that the intensity
would go negative,

00:38:43.070 --> 00:38:45.290
which is not possible.

00:38:45.290 --> 00:38:48.070
So this plots what it is--

00:38:48.070 --> 00:38:53.510
what you would see as
a function of delta phi

00:38:53.510 --> 00:38:57.110
and for a particular value of n.

00:38:57.110 --> 00:39:01.660
So there's some background,
sometimes called the bias.

00:39:01.660 --> 00:39:05.480
And then you've got some
wiggles on top of that.

00:39:05.480 --> 00:39:09.460
And so this plot is
plotted against delta phi.

00:39:09.460 --> 00:39:12.260
Delta phi could change by
a number of different ways,

00:39:12.260 --> 00:39:13.060
of course.

00:39:13.060 --> 00:39:16.450
One way it could change is if
you actually move the mirror.

00:39:16.450 --> 00:39:19.090
Another way it could change
is if you tilted the mirror.

00:39:19.090 --> 00:39:21.250
If you tilted the
mirror, then there'd

00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:24.070
be different delta phis
at different transverse

00:39:24.070 --> 00:39:26.050
positions on the mirror.

00:39:26.050 --> 00:39:32.390
And if we take Ar equal As, then
you've got perfect contrast,

00:39:32.390 --> 00:39:34.190
m equals 1.

00:39:34.190 --> 00:39:36.640
You see it goes
right down to zero.

00:39:36.640 --> 00:39:40.400
And that's the high
visibility of the fringes

00:39:40.400 --> 00:39:41.480
that you can get.

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:47.030
If, on the other hand,
you find that if you take,

00:39:47.030 --> 00:39:49.610
let's say, the
reference beam to be

00:39:49.610 --> 00:39:52.940
much stronger than
the signal beam,

00:39:52.940 --> 00:39:55.610
then you can see that m
is going to tend to zero.

00:39:55.610 --> 00:40:00.020
The contrast is going
to become very weak.

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:05.090
Actually, sometimes
people do do that.

00:40:05.090 --> 00:40:09.050
Contrast is not necessarily
the most important thing

00:40:09.050 --> 00:40:16.770
because if you notice what
we had before, you see that--

00:40:23.485 --> 00:40:25.367
let's go back to
the previous one.

00:40:28.880 --> 00:40:29.380
Yeah.

00:40:29.380 --> 00:40:31.120
Let's go back to this one here.

00:40:31.120 --> 00:40:34.580
You can see that you've
got these three terms.

00:40:34.580 --> 00:40:36.220
So what we're saying
is if you make

00:40:36.220 --> 00:40:41.970
Ar much bigger than As, then
you make the contrast is going

00:40:41.970 --> 00:40:44.170
to get smaller and
smaller because obviously

00:40:44.170 --> 00:40:47.500
this term is going to become
much bigger than this one.

00:40:47.500 --> 00:40:52.150
But nevertheless, it does
actually make this term bigger.

00:40:52.150 --> 00:40:55.210
So if actually what
you're trying to do

00:40:55.210 --> 00:40:59.470
is measure this signal in
some background of noise,

00:40:59.470 --> 00:41:04.450
it's sometimes a good thing
to make Ar bigger than As

00:41:04.450 --> 00:41:07.960
because as you increase Ar,
it increases the strength

00:41:07.960 --> 00:41:12.370
of this interference term.

00:41:12.370 --> 00:41:14.400
And that's the
principle that's used

00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:18.290
in heterodyne interferometry.

00:41:18.290 --> 00:41:24.110
So not always true that you try
and make the contrast as big

00:41:24.110 --> 00:41:25.160
as possible.

00:41:25.160 --> 00:41:26.407
Yeah.

00:41:26.407 --> 00:41:28.490
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: There
is one more factor of 2

00:41:28.490 --> 00:41:30.020
missing here.

00:41:30.020 --> 00:41:33.410
On the left-hand side bottom,
the swing of the fringes

00:41:33.410 --> 00:41:37.920
should be 2m times
i0 times-- yeah.

00:41:37.920 --> 00:41:41.240
There's a factor of 2 missing.

00:41:41.240 --> 00:41:42.260
That's quite unusual.

00:41:42.260 --> 00:41:43.620
Three slides in a row.

00:41:43.620 --> 00:41:46.060
They're all missing
a factor of 2.

00:41:46.060 --> 00:41:47.810
COLIN SHEPPARD: And
they don't cancel out.

00:41:47.810 --> 00:41:47.960
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yeah.

00:41:47.960 --> 00:41:48.460
I guess.

00:41:53.098 --> 00:41:53.890
COLIN SHEPPARD: OK.

00:41:53.890 --> 00:41:56.920
So that's the Michelson
interferometer.

00:41:56.920 --> 00:42:00.280
So the Michelson interferometer
is basically, you can see,

00:42:00.280 --> 00:42:02.890
a sort of reflection
interferometer.

00:42:02.890 --> 00:42:06.008
And we're now going to
go into the Mach-Zehnder

00:42:06.008 --> 00:42:08.050
interferometer, which is
basically a transmission

00:42:08.050 --> 00:42:09.230
interferometer.

00:42:09.230 --> 00:42:12.620
So the principle
is very similar.

00:42:12.620 --> 00:42:15.160
You split the light
into two parts.

00:42:15.160 --> 00:42:18.200
The two paths-- two light beams
go through different path,

00:42:18.200 --> 00:42:24.640
and then you combine
them onto a detector.

00:42:24.640 --> 00:42:27.680
So this works in
transmission mode.

00:42:27.680 --> 00:42:30.920
Here you're looking
through an object.

00:42:30.920 --> 00:42:33.080
So now you're not going
to get that factor of 2,

00:42:33.080 --> 00:42:37.400
of course, because the light
is only going through it once.

00:42:37.400 --> 00:42:39.890
So the light goes through here.

00:42:39.890 --> 00:42:43.550
You notice that the way
this has been drawn,

00:42:43.550 --> 00:42:47.750
it's been drawn so that this
light is going like this,

00:42:47.750 --> 00:42:50.040
this light is going like this.

00:42:50.040 --> 00:42:56.710
So you can see this path and
this path are roughly equal.

00:42:56.710 --> 00:43:01.720
You might equally-- well, you
could have thought of making

00:43:01.720 --> 00:43:05.540
this by doing it more like--

00:43:05.540 --> 00:43:06.280
couldn't you?

00:43:06.280 --> 00:43:14.500
You could have
done it like that.

00:43:17.840 --> 00:43:23.240
So where now you can see, if
we'd have made it like that,

00:43:23.240 --> 00:43:28.930
this path is obviously
longer than that path.

00:43:28.930 --> 00:43:35.250
So I guess nowadays if
you did that experiment

00:43:35.250 --> 00:43:39.240
with a laser which has
got a very long coherence

00:43:39.240 --> 00:43:42.390
length, something like a
frequency double YAG laser,

00:43:42.390 --> 00:43:44.040
this would work fine.

00:43:44.040 --> 00:43:48.780
If you tried doing this with
an arc lamp or something

00:43:48.780 --> 00:43:54.060
like that it wouldn't work
because this distance is

00:43:54.060 --> 00:43:58.410
much longer than the coherence
length of the source.

00:43:58.410 --> 00:44:02.400
So you're all used to the
idea that actually you

00:44:02.400 --> 00:44:04.380
don't see interference
fringes all the time.

00:44:04.380 --> 00:44:07.890
In the normal,
regular, everyday life

00:44:07.890 --> 00:44:10.620
you don't see interference
fringes very much.

00:44:10.620 --> 00:44:13.620
And that's because
in everyday life,

00:44:13.620 --> 00:44:17.640
normally the light is
incoherent rather than coherent.

00:44:17.640 --> 00:44:23.700
So if you make this system here
or the Michelson interferometer

00:44:23.700 --> 00:44:28.620
we showed before and you make
it so that these paths are

00:44:28.620 --> 00:44:32.840
accurately the same
length, then you

00:44:32.840 --> 00:44:37.085
could get interference
even with light from a--

00:44:37.085 --> 00:44:40.475
you can get interference even
from light from a tungsten lamp

00:44:40.475 --> 00:44:41.920
bulb.

00:44:41.920 --> 00:44:46.060
And they produce really
nice, beautiful fringes

00:44:46.060 --> 00:44:47.470
with different colors.

00:44:47.470 --> 00:44:52.810
Maybe my students maybe
have seen these in the lab.

00:44:52.810 --> 00:44:54.480
But anyway.

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:57.330
So here you can use this
to measure the optical path

00:44:57.330 --> 00:44:59.890
of some object.

00:44:59.890 --> 00:45:03.050
And yeah.

00:45:03.050 --> 00:45:08.960
So this is now, again,
looking at this idea

00:45:08.960 --> 00:45:10.720
of tilting something.

00:45:10.720 --> 00:45:14.450
I mentioned about tilting
with regard to the Michelson

00:45:14.450 --> 00:45:15.260
interferometer.

00:45:15.260 --> 00:45:17.600
I said, if you tilt
one of those mirrors,

00:45:17.600 --> 00:45:23.990
you would actually get the
optical path varying linearly

00:45:23.990 --> 00:45:26.430
with transverse distance.

00:45:26.430 --> 00:45:28.700
So if you actually
looked at an image

00:45:28.700 --> 00:45:31.010
of that interference,
what you would see

00:45:31.010 --> 00:45:34.580
would be a series of fringes.

00:45:34.580 --> 00:45:37.700
And the spacing
between the fringes

00:45:37.700 --> 00:45:41.490
would increase as you
increase the angle.

00:45:41.490 --> 00:45:43.440
So this is the same here.

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:48.110
We're getting the offset
between these two paths--

00:45:48.110 --> 00:45:55.220
these two beams-- by rotating
this mirror slightly.

00:45:55.220 --> 00:45:58.730
And then as you can see,
these two beams arrive

00:45:58.730 --> 00:46:01.470
on a CCD camera, it shows here.

00:46:01.470 --> 00:46:03.740
So you will actually--
in this case,

00:46:03.740 --> 00:46:07.910
you would get some
variation in intensity

00:46:07.910 --> 00:46:09.980
on this detector, which
you could actually

00:46:09.980 --> 00:46:11.960
measure with the detector.

00:46:11.960 --> 00:46:13.520
So it would look
something like this.

00:46:13.520 --> 00:46:17.150
This would now be,
then, a function of x

00:46:17.150 --> 00:46:20.870
rather than just being a
function of the optical path

00:46:20.870 --> 00:46:22.540
difference.

00:46:22.540 --> 00:46:27.590
So this bit here, I guess, is
explaining, is deriving that.

00:46:27.590 --> 00:46:30.540
So we're adding
two wave together.

00:46:30.540 --> 00:46:33.050
One is arriving normally.

00:46:33.050 --> 00:46:36.720
The other one is tilted
through an angle theta.

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:44.150
And so this one here is going
to have a linear phase variation

00:46:44.150 --> 00:46:48.575
as a function of x, which will
then appear inside this cosine.

00:46:51.980 --> 00:46:55.350
So finally what
we get here then,

00:46:55.350 --> 00:46:59.870
the value of this bit
here, the z cos theta,

00:46:59.870 --> 00:47:03.000
is just this constant here.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:07.850
So all that does is it shifts
these fringes this way.

00:47:07.850 --> 00:47:11.880
But normally, if you were
doing this experiment,

00:47:11.880 --> 00:47:15.050
one thing you could
do then very simply

00:47:15.050 --> 00:47:19.890
is to measure what this spatial
wavelength of these fringes is.

00:47:19.890 --> 00:47:23.850
And from that you
could, for example,

00:47:23.850 --> 00:47:25.250
if you knew all
the other things,

00:47:25.250 --> 00:47:27.680
you could measure what
this rotation theta was,

00:47:27.680 --> 00:47:28.820
couldn't you?

00:47:28.820 --> 00:47:31.700
If you knew what the
rotation theta is,

00:47:31.700 --> 00:47:33.980
then I don't know what
