00:59:07.670 --> 00:59:11.210
And then we're going to go
to a more complicated case

00:59:11.210 --> 00:59:13.670
of Fresnel diffraction.

00:59:16.600 --> 00:59:21.370
So first of all
Huygens' principle.

00:59:21.370 --> 00:59:25.580
So I think at the beginning
of the lecture course,

00:59:25.580 --> 00:59:29.840
George said a bit about
the history of how

00:59:29.840 --> 00:59:34.130
Huygens' came up with this
idea quite a long time ago,

00:59:34.130 --> 00:59:34.630
wasn't it?

00:59:34.630 --> 00:59:36.580
It was even before
Newton or around--

00:59:36.580 --> 00:59:39.880
I think slightly before but
around the same time as Newton.

00:59:39.880 --> 00:59:43.900
So when people
still hadn't really

00:59:43.900 --> 00:59:47.920
decided whether light
was a wave or a particle.

00:59:47.920 --> 00:59:49.860
And of course, we
still haven't decided.

00:59:49.860 --> 00:59:53.260
So times don't change, really.

00:59:53.260 --> 00:59:56.680
But anyway so probably
now, looking back,

00:59:56.680 --> 01:00:01.130
we could say that Newton was
the first quantum opticist.

01:00:01.130 --> 01:00:03.010
But anyway.

01:00:03.010 --> 01:00:06.220
So this was this
was Huygens' idea.

01:00:06.220 --> 01:00:10.570
He was saying that if you
think of a light beam--

01:00:10.570 --> 01:00:14.620
a wave propagating in space,
then at some moment in time

01:00:14.620 --> 01:00:18.050
this is a wavefront.

01:00:18.050 --> 01:00:21.890
The wavefront is a
surface of constant phase.

01:00:21.890 --> 01:00:29.900
And he came up with this model
for how light propagates where

01:00:29.900 --> 01:00:35.420
he assumed that all the
points on this wavefront

01:00:35.420 --> 01:00:38.030
can be thought of as
being a source of what

01:00:38.030 --> 01:00:40.080
he called secondary wavelets.

01:00:40.080 --> 01:00:44.690
So each of these points
radiates like a spherical wave.

01:00:44.690 --> 01:00:48.650
And then if you sum those
all up and calculate

01:00:48.650 --> 01:00:52.950
what the effect is at some
distance in front here,

01:00:52.950 --> 01:00:58.110
then that would then predict
what that wavefront--

01:00:58.110 --> 01:01:02.750
what the wave had done
at a slightly later time.

01:01:02.750 --> 01:01:04.940
So that's the principle.

01:01:04.940 --> 01:01:09.440
And so quite a
simple idea, really.

01:01:09.440 --> 01:01:16.100
And you can come up with a very
simple mathematical description

01:01:16.100 --> 01:01:17.240
of it.

01:01:17.240 --> 01:01:19.940
Unfortunately, it doesn't
work marvelously well.

01:01:19.940 --> 01:01:23.420
And people put a lot
of effort into trying

01:01:23.420 --> 01:01:25.610
to improve the theory.

01:01:25.610 --> 01:01:30.560
And they came up with
some rather arbitrary--

01:01:30.560 --> 01:01:32.480
they seem rather arbitrary--

01:01:32.480 --> 01:01:35.420
factors that they had
to include in order

01:01:35.420 --> 01:01:36.960
to get it to work properly.

01:01:36.960 --> 01:01:40.250
So I think nowadays we probably
look back over all this

01:01:40.250 --> 01:01:42.500
and think it was just history.

01:01:42.500 --> 01:01:46.310
And there are better ways of
really tackling the problem.

01:01:46.310 --> 01:01:50.240
But anyway, at the very
simple level though,

01:01:50.240 --> 01:01:55.350
it's still a nice simple
theory for how you do that.

01:01:55.350 --> 01:01:58.070
So if you want to calculate
what the field is at this point

01:01:58.070 --> 01:02:00.200
here, say, you look
at all these waves

01:02:00.200 --> 01:02:02.840
that come from all these
points on the wavefront,

01:02:02.840 --> 01:02:05.980
add them all together
as phases, of course,

01:02:05.980 --> 01:02:08.110
and that will give you
the field at that point.

01:02:11.640 --> 01:02:14.270
And there it's showing
how you do that.

01:02:14.270 --> 01:02:17.420
And then you can do it
again and again and again

01:02:17.420 --> 01:02:19.040
and show how the
wave propagates.

01:02:21.790 --> 01:02:25.930
So example, a hole
in an opaque screen.

01:02:25.930 --> 01:02:28.900
So I guess this is pretty
well the simplest example

01:02:28.900 --> 01:02:31.660
you could possibly think of.

01:02:31.660 --> 01:02:33.790
Well, no, I suppose the
opaque screen with no hole

01:02:33.790 --> 01:02:35.050
in would be even simpler.

