as being binary quantities.

01:14:58.010 --> 01:15:01.380
They might only have
two different values.

01:15:01.380 --> 01:15:04.040
For example, you might
have black and white,

01:15:04.040 --> 01:15:08.930
or they might be gray scale-type
continuously varying-type

01:15:08.930 --> 01:15:11.550
quantities.

01:15:11.550 --> 01:15:15.740
And then the phase also
you can think of that--

01:15:15.740 --> 01:15:19.820
maybe it's continuously
varying phase change,

01:15:19.820 --> 01:15:22.880
or it might have
just two values,

01:15:22.880 --> 01:15:28.910
binary values, or it might even
have multiple values maybe,

01:15:28.910 --> 01:15:29.870
say eight values.

01:15:29.870 --> 01:15:35.570
You can code-- people often
use transparencies like this

01:15:35.570 --> 01:15:42.740
to code binary numbers
up to some basis of eight

01:15:42.740 --> 01:15:45.970
or something like that.

01:15:45.970 --> 01:15:51.970
So if these assumptions
are true, then

01:15:51.970 --> 01:15:57.310
according to Huygens' principle
the propagation through this,

01:15:57.310 --> 01:16:02.530
all it's going to do
basically is change the--

01:16:02.530 --> 01:16:04.670
this is going to change to this.

01:16:04.670 --> 01:16:06.430
This is going to change to this.

01:16:06.430 --> 01:16:09.670
And you're not going
to get this affecting

01:16:09.670 --> 01:16:14.410
this very much if this
assumption of this thickness

01:16:14.410 --> 01:16:20.340
being very thin is valid,
in which case all it does--

01:16:20.340 --> 01:16:22.180
all this transparency does--

01:16:22.180 --> 01:16:28.000
is multiplies the field
going in by the transmission

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:33.250
of the grating to give
the amplitude of the wave

01:16:33.250 --> 01:16:34.360
as it comes out.

01:16:34.360 --> 01:16:39.010
So g minus is the wave-- is the
amplitude on the way in. g plus

01:16:39.010 --> 01:16:43.000
is the amplitude of the
wave on the way out.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:46.240
And this transmittances,
we call this

01:16:46.240 --> 01:16:49.210
the amplitude transmittance
of the grating.

01:16:49.210 --> 01:16:52.310
And you see it's a
function of position.

01:16:52.310 --> 01:16:58.300
And as we just described, it can
be broken up into an absorption

01:16:58.300 --> 01:17:01.830
term and a phase term.

01:17:01.830 --> 01:17:05.640
And as we just said, those
two might either be--

01:17:05.640 --> 01:17:08.340
they could be binary or they
could be continuously variable.

01:17:15.920 --> 01:17:16.420
Yes.

