So you can think of diffraction
then as being like interference

01:18:24.080 --> 01:18:25.430
with many, many beams.

01:18:36.010 --> 01:18:36.510
Yeah.

01:18:36.510 --> 01:18:38.090
So this is saying,
just like we said

01:18:38.090 --> 01:18:44.090
before, we are describing
this interference

01:18:44.090 --> 01:18:45.740
of these many, many beams now.

01:18:45.740 --> 01:18:52.610
When we did the Young's
experiment, each of the slits

01:18:52.610 --> 01:18:54.560
was described by
a delta function

01:18:54.560 --> 01:18:57.050
at a particular position.

01:18:57.050 --> 01:18:59.510
And now we're saying
that in general, we

01:18:59.510 --> 01:19:04.970
can think of this as not being
just two slits but an integral

01:19:04.970 --> 01:19:09.680
over many, many apertures--

01:19:09.680 --> 01:19:15.890
very small apertures--
placed at these points x1 y1.

01:19:15.890 --> 01:19:18.860
Sorry, placed at the
points xy, I guess.

01:19:18.860 --> 01:19:23.450
And then we're integrating
over all those points in order

01:19:23.450 --> 01:19:28.880
to get the total effect of
all those spherical waves.

01:19:28.880 --> 01:19:31.250
This is now we're
saying that g--

01:19:33.830 --> 01:19:39.140
so this is g minus after the--

01:19:39.140 --> 01:19:42.980
it's just saying that g--

01:19:42.980 --> 01:19:46.807
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: [INAUDIBLE]

01:19:46.807 --> 01:19:48.890
COLIN SHEPPARD: This is
just the shifting theorem.

01:19:48.890 --> 01:19:51.040
And now we're going to
state that in there, are we?

01:19:51.040 --> 01:20:01.175
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: [INAUDIBLE]

01:20:01.175 --> 01:20:02.050
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah.

01:20:02.050 --> 01:20:05.185
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: [INAUDIBLE]

01:20:05.185 --> 01:20:06.060
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah.

01:20:06.060 --> 01:20:06.430
Yeah.

01:20:06.430 --> 01:20:06.980
OK.

01:20:06.980 --> 01:20:07.290
Yeah.

01:20:07.290 --> 01:20:07.780
Yeah.

01:20:07.780 --> 01:20:08.280
Yeah.

01:20:20.390 --> 01:20:23.180
So this is what goes in then.

01:20:23.180 --> 01:20:29.690
So this is our single point
on the wavefront going in.

01:20:29.690 --> 01:20:33.710
And this gives rise to
a wave that comes out,

01:20:33.710 --> 01:20:37.100
a spherical wave that comes
out, which is of this form.

01:20:37.100 --> 01:20:39.950
It's the same as this
multiplied by the transmission

01:20:39.950 --> 01:20:41.450
of the source.

01:20:41.450 --> 01:20:46.312
And then this then radiates
like a spherical wave.

01:20:46.312 --> 01:20:48.770
And then you're going to get
some distribution of amplitude

01:20:48.770 --> 01:20:52.040
on this observation plane,
which is going to be exactly

01:20:52.040 --> 01:20:54.120
the same as we had before.

01:20:54.120 --> 01:20:55.360
And we've got this--

01:20:55.360 --> 01:20:57.950
again, we've got
this parabolic phase

01:20:57.950 --> 01:21:03.600
function that comes from
the Fresnel approximation.

01:21:03.600 --> 01:21:08.920
So it assumes that x dashed y
dashed are much smaller than z.

01:21:13.030 --> 01:21:16.320
So that's for a single point.

01:21:16.320 --> 01:21:19.610
And now we do-- now we
integrate over all of these.

01:21:19.610 --> 01:21:22.790
And the final result
for the amplitude

01:21:22.790 --> 01:21:26.590
we'll see on the screen is
given by this expression then.

01:21:26.590 --> 01:21:29.090
So this is the
incident wave, this

01:21:29.090 --> 01:21:31.760
is the transmission
of the screen,

01:21:31.760 --> 01:21:35.210
and this is the
bit that describes

01:21:35.210 --> 01:21:38.420
the propagation of
the spherical waves

01:21:38.420 --> 01:21:41.600
according to the
Fresnel approximation.

01:21:45.940 --> 01:21:46.760
So yeah.

01:21:46.760 --> 01:21:51.170
So this result is known as the
Fresnel diffraction integral,

01:21:51.170 --> 01:21:53.090
or simply the Fresnel integral.

01:21:53.090 --> 01:22:00.850
And so I mentioned earlier that
this approximation, replacing

01:22:00.850 --> 01:22:02.690
the square root by
the squared terms,

01:22:02.690 --> 01:22:05.000
is called the Fresnel
approximation.

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:06.260
So all of these--

01:22:06.260 --> 01:22:08.300
Fresnel gets the name
of all of these things.

01:22:15.490 --> 01:22:15.990
Yeah.

01:22:15.990 --> 01:22:20.170
This is just pointing out that
this expression we've just

01:22:20.170 --> 01:22:24.010
written down, the form
of this is exactly

01:22:24.010 --> 01:22:27.620
the form of a convolution.

01:22:27.620 --> 01:22:33.400
And so that's a very
important result.

01:22:33.400 --> 01:22:36.800
A convolution, of course, means
it's space invariant, doesn't

01:22:36.800 --> 01:22:37.300
it?

01:22:37.300 --> 01:22:41.350
It means that you
can write this--

01:22:41.350 --> 01:22:45.100
it's what goes in convolved
with something which is

01:22:45.100 --> 01:22:48.140
independent of the coordinates.

01:22:48.140 --> 01:22:51.530
And so if you think of
this as a convolution,

01:22:51.530 --> 01:22:56.080
the thing you have to
convolve with is this thing.

01:22:56.080 --> 01:23:01.900
So you can think of
this as being like--

01:23:01.900 --> 01:23:03.640
well, it's called
the point spread

01:23:03.640 --> 01:23:06.260
function or the amplitude
point spread function.

01:23:06.260 --> 01:23:12.310
So if you put in some amplitude
and convolve it with this,

01:23:12.310 --> 01:23:13.720
then you'll get something out.

01:23:27.100 --> 01:23:29.560
So this is explaining
what I just said.

01:23:29.560 --> 01:23:33.610
So this is the sort
of behavior that you

01:23:33.610 --> 01:23:38.410
think of when you're looking
at a mechanical or electrical

01:23:38.410 --> 01:23:38.980
systems.

01:23:38.980 --> 01:23:42.910
You can think of a system
of being like a black box,

01:23:42.910 --> 01:23:45.490
or in this case, a blue box.

01:23:45.490 --> 01:23:49.420
And something goes in
and something comes out.

01:23:49.420 --> 01:23:53.650
And we don't have to worry
too much about what's in here.

01:23:53.650 --> 01:23:56.920
But you can express what goes
in, of course, either in terms

01:23:56.920 --> 01:24:01.540
of some sort of impulse
response function,

01:24:01.540 --> 01:24:04.150
or as we'll come to
in later lectures,

01:24:04.150 --> 01:24:08.390
as some sort of transfer
function-type behavior.

01:24:08.390 --> 01:24:11.650
But at the moment, we're
doing in the spatial domain.

01:24:11.650 --> 01:24:17.120
So if we convolve this with
this point spread function,

01:24:17.120 --> 01:24:19.630
then we'll get this
output, like this.

01:24:26.900 --> 01:24:30.970
Now we go on to do
some examples of this.

01:24:30.970 --> 01:24:34.450
And this is probably the
most important example--

01:24:34.450 --> 01:24:36.250
comes up all the time--

01:24:36.250 --> 01:24:41.660
because lots of optical
components are circular.

01:24:41.660 --> 01:24:47.240
So lenses and so on, very often
they've got this circular form.

01:24:47.240 --> 01:24:51.980
And so this comes up
time and time again.

01:24:51.980 --> 01:24:56.890
And so all we've got to
do now then is we put in--

01:24:56.890 --> 01:25:02.570
we say that our amplitude
after the light's gone

01:25:02.570 --> 01:25:09.200
through this circular aperture
is 1 inside the circle

01:25:09.200 --> 01:25:10.845
and 0 outside the circle.

01:25:13.540 --> 01:25:16.960
And so that Fresnel
diffraction integral

01:25:16.960 --> 01:25:20.140
that we have to work out
for this circular aperture

01:25:20.140 --> 01:25:25.150
is just 1 inside and 0 outside.

01:25:25.150 --> 01:25:28.360
So it's just-- you
just have to do

01:25:28.360 --> 01:25:30.430
the integral over the inside.

01:25:30.430 --> 01:25:34.390
So this is just over
the values of x and y

01:25:34.390 --> 01:25:36.820
that are inside the
bright part here.

01:25:39.330 --> 01:25:43.560
Now, so unfortunately, that
integral is a bit hard to do.

01:25:43.560 --> 01:25:47.670
So we're not going to do it
at the moment in general.

01:25:47.670 --> 01:25:52.710
But we will do a very simple
example, a special case

01:25:52.710 --> 01:25:55.510
of what happens along the axis.

01:25:55.510 --> 01:26:03.410
So if we put x and y
both zero, now we get--

01:26:03.410 --> 01:26:07.670
we put x dashed equals
0, y dashed equals 0.

01:26:07.670 --> 01:26:10.560
The integral comes down to this.

01:26:10.560 --> 01:26:14.450
And now that is an
integral we can do.

01:26:14.450 --> 01:26:16.625
And it's an integral that
probably a lot of you

01:26:16.625 --> 01:26:18.410
have come across before.

01:26:18.410 --> 01:26:22.740
The way to solve that is to
go into polar coordinates.

01:26:22.740 --> 01:26:27.390
And so if you change
into polar coordinates,

01:26:27.390 --> 01:26:29.730
you've got a theta and a phi--

01:26:29.730 --> 01:26:33.030
a theta and a rho part.

01:26:33.030 --> 01:26:36.230
The theta part is just an
integral of a constant,

01:26:36.230 --> 01:26:38.640
so that just becomes 2 pi.

01:26:38.640 --> 01:26:42.760
And the integral of this
other thing you can now do.

01:26:42.760 --> 01:26:46.310
Integral of rho e to
the i rho squared over

01:26:46.310 --> 01:26:49.400
something you can do
because the rho outside

01:26:49.400 --> 01:26:54.550
is the differential
of the bit inside.

01:26:54.550 --> 01:26:58.270
So to actually do
that properly, you

01:26:58.270 --> 01:27:01.310
can make a substitution then.

01:27:01.310 --> 01:27:04.910
Make a substitution that
xi is equal to this thing

01:27:04.910 --> 01:27:06.740
inside here.

01:27:06.740 --> 01:27:09.980
And after you've made
that substitution,

01:27:09.980 --> 01:27:14.690
you now just get integral
of e to the i xi.

01:27:14.690 --> 01:27:20.690
So that's something
you can just do.

01:27:20.690 --> 01:27:22.520
And you get an answer.

01:27:34.630 --> 01:27:35.130
Yeah.

01:27:35.130 --> 01:27:36.660
Notice that you get--

01:27:36.660 --> 01:27:41.490
so this final result
here, this term

01:27:41.490 --> 01:27:45.510
here is just the phase
term as a function of z.

01:27:45.510 --> 01:27:49.320
So that's just what you would
get if it was just a wave

01:27:49.320 --> 01:27:51.570
moving in free space.

01:27:51.570 --> 01:27:54.210
And then these other
two terms, notice,

01:27:54.210 --> 01:27:55.920
they're exactly the same form.

01:27:55.920 --> 01:28:00.300
This is an e to the i
something, and this is a sine

01:28:00.300 --> 01:28:01.410
of exactly the same thing.

01:28:08.120 --> 01:28:10.920
So that's what we get.

01:28:10.920 --> 01:28:13.470
As I say, if you
go back to this,

01:28:13.470 --> 01:28:15.360
if you wanted to do
this integral here,

01:28:15.360 --> 01:28:17.670
it's a bit more complicated.

01:28:17.670 --> 01:28:20.870
And so we're not going
to do that at the moment.

01:28:20.870 --> 01:28:25.488
But I guess eventually we
have to do something about it.

01:28:25.488 --> 01:28:28.103
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: [INAUDIBLE]

01:28:28.103 --> 01:28:29.020
COLIN SHEPPARD: Right.

01:28:29.020 --> 01:28:33.520
So if we look at this
amplitude along the axis,

01:28:33.520 --> 01:28:37.750
then, you can see it's got this
sinusoidal sort of behavior.

01:28:37.750 --> 01:28:40.840
If you looked at the
intensity, this would just go,

01:28:40.840 --> 01:28:42.850
and you just get sine
squared of something.

01:28:42.850 --> 01:28:47.350
Sine squared as a function
of a constant over z.

01:28:47.350 --> 01:28:50.620
So as it points out
here, then, it's

01:28:50.620 --> 01:28:54.820
going to have peaks
and nulls, maxima

01:28:54.820 --> 01:28:59.650
and minima, corresponding to
these particular values of z.

01:28:59.650 --> 01:29:04.210
So you'll get a
sinusoidal variation

01:29:04.210 --> 01:29:08.140
in amplitude along the axis.

01:29:08.140 --> 01:29:10.465
The other thing
to note is that--

01:29:13.640 --> 01:29:14.660
where's it gone?

01:29:19.980 --> 01:29:21.450
Yeah.

01:29:21.450 --> 01:29:26.790
Notice that this z and
this z canceled out.

01:29:26.790 --> 01:29:32.700
This z here appeared when
we made this substitution.

01:29:32.700 --> 01:29:36.960
And so these z's finally cancel.

01:29:36.960 --> 01:29:41.940
And so the final result
has got no z in it.

01:29:41.940 --> 01:29:45.570
Sorry, no z in the
modulus part term.

01:29:45.570 --> 01:29:48.450
So you've got this
series of fringes

01:29:48.450 --> 01:29:54.060
which are of constant
amplitude however

01:29:54.060 --> 01:29:56.340
far away from this
aperture you go,

01:29:56.340 --> 01:29:58.860
which might seem
rather surprising.

01:29:58.860 --> 01:30:02.280
You might think that as you
got closer to the aperture,

01:30:02.280 --> 01:30:06.540
it would get
brighter, might you?

01:30:06.540 --> 01:30:07.800
But it doesn't, it seems.

01:30:10.688 --> 01:30:13.230
I'm just trying to think quickly
why that should be the case.

01:30:17.010 --> 01:30:18.610
But I'm sure it is true.

01:30:22.400 --> 01:30:24.950
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Notice
also the pi over 2 phase shift

01:30:24.950 --> 01:30:28.440
has disappeared.

01:30:28.440 --> 01:30:30.415
It got eaten up by the sine.

01:30:30.415 --> 01:30:31.290
COLIN SHEPPARD: Yeah.

01:30:31.290 --> 01:30:31.800
That's true.

01:30:31.800 --> 01:30:32.130
Sorry.

01:30:32.130 --> 01:30:33.040
I didn't mention that.

01:30:33.040 --> 01:30:33.460
Yeah.

01:30:33.460 --> 01:30:33.960
OK.

01:30:33.960 --> 01:30:37.710
So when you put in the limits
of the integration, then

01:30:37.710 --> 01:30:39.340
you've got this minus this.

01:30:39.340 --> 01:30:41.550
And this we replaced by sine.

01:30:41.550 --> 01:30:45.580
But of course we need to get
an extra i to get the sine.

01:30:45.580 --> 01:30:46.080
Yeah.

01:30:46.080 --> 01:30:49.260
So the pi over 2 phase
shift is also gone.

01:30:49.260 --> 01:30:52.620
The other thing that perhaps
is worth mentioning also

01:30:52.620 --> 01:30:56.760
is that when we got down
to this integral of course,

01:30:56.760 --> 01:30:58.740
this is just the
Fourier transform of 1,

01:30:58.740 --> 01:31:00.860
isn't it, within this region.

01:31:00.860 --> 01:31:05.710
It's the Fourier transform
of a rect function.

01:31:05.710 --> 01:31:10.780
And even if we looked at
more complicated example,

01:31:10.780 --> 01:31:13.290
if you add this circular
symmetry, whatever

01:31:13.290 --> 01:31:19.500
this amplitude transmittance
of this aperture had been,

01:31:19.500 --> 01:31:22.620
all we'd have to do is to
do the Fourier transform

01:31:22.620 --> 01:31:26.400
of that amplitude
transmittances of that aperture

01:31:26.400 --> 01:31:30.810
as a function of
this coordinate xi.

01:31:30.810 --> 01:31:34.320
So that's a sort of trick
you can use to calculate

01:31:34.320 --> 01:31:36.600
these things easily sometimes.

01:31:36.600 --> 01:31:39.630
I think we're here
for the movies now.

01:31:39.630 --> 01:31:44.130
So MATLAB has calculated
these things for us.

01:31:44.130 --> 01:31:46.740
And when I press the
button, it will go.

01:31:46.740 --> 01:31:49.230
But I'm not going to press
it until you're ready, just

01:31:49.230 --> 01:31:51.010
in case it's very quick.

01:31:51.010 --> 01:31:54.150
So this is a big aperture.

01:31:54.150 --> 01:31:56.700
So what you'll see
is how the wave

01:31:56.700 --> 01:31:59.640
propagates from that aperture.

01:31:59.640 --> 01:32:01.720
This is actually
quite a big aperture.

01:32:01.720 --> 01:32:05.230
So you don't expect to see a
lot of diffraction in this case.

01:32:05.230 --> 01:32:08.220
When we come to this one,
this is a small aperture.

01:32:08.220 --> 01:32:10.920
And as we said before, the
smaller it is to start,

01:32:10.920 --> 01:32:13.110
the more it's going to spread.

01:32:13.110 --> 01:32:16.440
So you're going to see a
lot more effect on that one.

01:32:16.440 --> 01:32:18.900
And so you have to
look quite closely

01:32:18.900 --> 01:32:23.630
to see what happens
as it propagates.

01:32:23.630 --> 01:32:26.900
So this is a radius
of 40 lambda.

01:32:26.900 --> 01:32:29.120
Now you can see some sort
of fringes appearing,

01:32:29.120 --> 01:32:35.230
and it becomes like a bright
halo around the edges.

01:32:35.230 --> 01:32:36.760
And if you look
very closely, you'll

01:32:36.760 --> 01:32:39.700
see quite a lot of
fine structure on this.

01:32:42.780 --> 01:32:47.870
And then the small one,
this is 10 wavelengths.

01:32:47.870 --> 01:32:50.530
So this one changes
a lot quicker.

01:32:50.530 --> 01:32:53.598
You see it's doing
quite drastic things.

01:32:53.598 --> 01:32:55.390
By the time it gets to
the end, you've even

01:32:55.390 --> 01:32:56.820
got a black spot in the center.

01:33:03.190 --> 01:33:05.730
The fact that, of course--

01:33:08.600 --> 01:33:11.650
we said before that the
smaller the aperture,

01:33:11.650 --> 01:33:14.770
the more it spreads, but
also the quicker it spreads.

01:33:14.770 --> 01:33:16.780
So you can see that
actually this one

01:33:16.780 --> 01:33:19.000
has got a lot further
in the development

01:33:19.000 --> 01:33:20.920
of the pattern than this one.

01:33:20.920 --> 01:33:24.820
This one still looks roughly
similar to what it started as.

01:33:24.820 --> 01:33:27.024
This one is looking
very, very different.

01:33:35.217 --> 01:33:36.550
It calls this the blinking spot.

01:33:36.550 --> 01:33:38.550
I've never heard of it
called the blinking spot.

01:33:38.550 --> 01:33:39.270
But anyway.

