Yeah.

01:34:02.200 --> 01:34:03.770
Yeah.

01:34:03.770 --> 01:34:04.270
OK.

01:34:04.270 --> 01:34:07.140
So now the rectangular aperture.

01:34:07.140 --> 01:34:11.980
The rectangular aperture--
actually it turns out you

01:34:11.980 --> 01:34:13.810
can't get a simple
expression for what

01:34:13.810 --> 01:34:17.500
happens along the axis
of the rectangular case,

01:34:17.500 --> 01:34:19.660
unlike the circular case.

01:34:19.660 --> 01:34:22.380
So that's probably why
George hasn't done it.

01:34:22.380 --> 01:34:26.980
And so you can get expressions
in terms of Fresnel integrals

01:34:26.980 --> 01:34:29.440
for everywhere, in
fact, for this case.

01:34:29.440 --> 01:34:31.090
So the square case, then.

01:34:31.090 --> 01:34:32.530
Let's see what that does.

01:34:32.530 --> 01:34:33.970
The big square.

01:34:33.970 --> 01:34:38.790
Again, you can see-- you can
see some sort of fringes.

01:34:38.790 --> 01:34:41.380
And by the time it's
got to the end here,

01:34:41.380 --> 01:34:45.460
you can see bright lines around
the edges, and also bright

01:34:45.460 --> 01:34:48.480
spots in the four corners.

01:34:48.480 --> 01:34:54.130
And then if we look
at the small square,

01:34:54.130 --> 01:34:56.470
again, it's changing
